GAME SPEED AND PRESETS
  How to tune Empire 5 for different play styles.

OVERVIEW
  Two settings control the overall pace of the game:

    etu_per_update         — game time per update tick (ETU = Empire Time Units)
    update_interval_secs   — real-world seconds between update ticks

  Changing either one affects how the game FEELS.  But several other
  parameters were designed for a specific ETU value in 4.4.1 (etu=8).
  If you change etu_per_update without adjusting the related constants,
  education swings too violently, population grows too fast, and the
  game feels wrong.  The presets in configs/ handle all of this for you.

PRESET CONFIGURATIONS
  Four ready-to-use preset files are in configs/:

    configs/blitz.toml      etu=20, update every 10 min,  game lasts 1-2 days
    configs/weekend.toml    etu=40, update every 30 min,  game lasts a weekend
    configs/standard.toml   etu=60, update every 1 hour,  game lasts 1-3 weeks
    configs/longterm.toml   etu=96, update every 24 hours, game lasts 1-3 months

  To use a preset, copy it to your data directory and pass it with --config,
  or merge it into your empire.toml alongside your [server] and [limits] blocks.

PARAMETERS THAT MUST SCALE WITH etu_per_update
  These constants have values that assume a specific ETU rate.  They must
  be adjusted whenever etu_per_update changes or the game feel breaks.

  edu_avg (ETU education moving-average window)
    Controls how quickly education responds to changes in library output.
    Rule: edu_avg = 8 × etu_per_update
    Calibration: 8 update cycles to reach equilibrium from zero.
    Too low: one missed LCM delivery drops education sharply.
    Too high: libraries take many updates before education moves at all.

  hap_avg (ETU happiness moving-average window)
    Same idea as edu_avg but for parks/happiness.
    Rule: hap_avg = 2 × etu_per_update
    Calibration: 2 update cycles to equilibrium — happiness responds faster.

  obrate (civilian birth rate per ETU)
    The 4.4.1 default (0.005/ETU) was tuned for etu=8, giving 4% growth
    per update.  At etu=60 it gives 30% per update — sectors hit maxpop
    in 2 updates and stay there.
    Rule: obrate = 0.04 / etu_per_update   (keeps 4% growth per update)
    Note: the compiled-in default (0.005) matches 4.4.1 etu=8 behaviour.
          The presets use the scaled value for more gradual population curves.

  uwbrate (uncompensated worker birth rate per ETU)
    Same relationship as obrate, at half the rate.
    Rule: uwbrate = 0.02 / etu_per_update

PARAMETERS THAT ARE ALREADY IN ABSOLUTE ETU TERMS (no scaling needed)
  These use ETU as units directly — they express "N ETUs of game time" —
  so they stay consistent across different update frequencies.

  level_age_rate
    "Tech and research decay 1% per level_age_rate ETUs."
    Default 96 means 1% decay per 96 ETU of game time.
    At etu=60 that is one update every 1.6 ticks.
    At etu=96 (longterm) that is exactly 1% per update.
    You can raise this for very slow games where you want tech to persist.

  eatrate, babyeat, fcrate, fgrate
    All expressed per ETU.  They scale naturally with ETU and do not need
    adjustment.  Raise fcrate/fgrate slightly for resource-poor maps.

SCALING TABLE — quick reference
  etu_per_update | interval   | edu_avg | hap_avg | obrate   | uwbrate
  ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
       20        |  10 min    |   160   |    40   | 0.002    | 0.001
       40        |  30 min    |   320   |    80   | 0.001    | 0.0005
       60        |   1 hour   |   480   |   120   | 0.000667 | 0.000333
       96        |  24 hours  |   768   |   192   | 0.000417 | 0.000208

WORLD GENERATION PARAMETERS (fairland)
  Resource richness affects how fast nations can advance, regardless of
  update timing.  These are set when the world is created with fairland,
  not in empire.toml.

  Key fairland flags:
    -R seed     — random seed (use the same seed for reproducible worlds)
    -s          — resource density (higher = richer world, faster tech)
    -c count    — number of starting countries
    -l size     — land percentage

  For blitz games: use a denser, smaller world so players meet quickly.
  For long-term games: larger, sparser world with more room to expand.

  Resource balance tips:
    - More oil fields near capitals = faster tech center ramp-up
    - Higher min (iron) deposits = faster LCM production chain
    - Moderate gold (dust) = sustainable tech without trivial advancement

EXAMPLE: running TekBot as a standard game
  The docker/empire.toml on TekBot already uses etu=60.
  Merge the [rates] section from configs/standard.toml into it to get
  the proper scaled obrate.  Or override just the rates you want:

    [rates]
    edu_avg  = 480.0
    hap_avg  = 120.0
    obrate   = 0.000667
    uwbrate  = 0.000333

